<?xml-stylesheet type="text/xsl" href="edition.xsl"?><TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">
  <teiHeader>
    <fileDesc>
      <titleStmt>
        <title xml:lang="ta"><term xml:lang="en">Canto 2:</term> ūralaruraittakātai </title>
        <title type="sub">The Canto in which Gossip in the City is Reported (75 lines)</title>
      </titleStmt>
      <publicationStmt>
        <p/>
      </publicationStmt>
      <sourceDesc>
        <msDesc xml:lang="en">
          <msIdentifier>
          </msIdentifier>
          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>2.1-9 Mātavi's mother Cittirāpati, upset about the gossip that has arisen as a
                result of Maṇimēkalai's and her absence from the Indra Festival, summons Mātavi's
                confidante Vayantamālai to deliver a message to her. </p>

              <p>2.10-17 Vayantamālai finds Mātavi and Maṇimēkalai in the pavillion. They are
                weakened by asceticism. She asks what has happened.</p>

              <p>2.18-32 Vayantamālai lists Mātavi's attainments as a dancer, to remind her of her
                true calling.</p>

              <p>2.33-36 Vayantamālai tells Mātavi that to avoid shaming gossip she must give up
                her asceticism.</p>

              <p>2.37-41 Mātavi replies that since losing her lover Kōvalaṉ she has renounced shame.</p>

              <p>2.42-48 Mātavi lists the options open to widows: spontaneous death, the pyre, or
                penance.</p>

              <p>2.49-55b Mātavi cites Kaṇṇaki as a paragon of female virtue. </p>

              <p>2.55c -57 Mātavi states her wish that Maṇimēkalai, who is Kaṇṇaki's daughter (by
                marriage), renounce the courtesan life and become a nun.</p>

              <p>2.58-69 Mātavi recounts how, after the death of Kōvalaṉ, she went to a Buddhist
                teacher, Aṟavaṇa for instruction.</p>

              <p>2.70-75 Mātavi concludes her speech to Vayantamālai with a request to report her
                decision to Cittirāpati and the other women. Having failed to convince Mātavi,
                Vayantamālai returns in despair to Cittirāpati.</p>


            </summary>
          </msContents>
        </msDesc>
      </sourceDesc>
    </fileDesc>
